    "faq_8H9hGJ": {
      "type": "faq",
      "blocks": {
        "text_MbVxKt": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "High Antioxidant Activity",
            "answer": "<p>Mad honey (from Rhododendron spp.) contains grayanotoxins and phenolic compounds, giving it stronger antioxidant effects than many other honeys (Buratti et al., 2016).</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_rU3GYT": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Potential Anti-Cancer Properties (In Vitro)",
            "answer": "<p>Rhododendron extracts have shown inhibition of cancer cell growth in lab studies, though human trials are lacking (Miyata et al., 2011).</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_rJFcCF": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Gastrointestinal Benefits",
            "answer": "<p>Traditionally used for peptic ulcers, dyspepsia, and gastritis, possibly due to anti-inflammatory and antibacterial effects (Silici & Atayoglu, 2015).</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_HnYx74": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Cardiovascular Effects",
            "answer": "<p>Grayanotoxins cause vagus nerve overstimulation, leading to temporary lower blood pressure and reduced heart rate, which may benefit hypertension in controlled doses (Gunduz et al., 2008).</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_7LgTDR": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Analgesic (pain relief)",
            "answer": "<p>Exhibited significant pain-reducing effects in mice with acute and neuropathic pain. Reference :- Pharmacology Biochemistry and Behavior, 2013 study on diabetic neuropathy</p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_MbVxKt",
        "text_rU3GYT",
