    "faq_yp3Czd": {
      "type": "faq",
      "blocks": {
        "text_iMiPVV": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What mental and neurological benefits does Mad honey have?",
            "answer": "<p>Mad Honey can promote relaxation and mild stress relief which can help shut down the release of stress chemicals. This can be a mental and neurological benefit of the Mad Honey but be aware that Mad Honey doesn’t directly help repair nerve damage.</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_4axeRH": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What diseases does Mad honey help?",
            "answer": "<p>Although there has not been clinically proven tests regarding the use of Mad Honey for curing any sort of disease. But the Mad Honey does have been recorded to have been used for the treatment of several alignments like Cold, Flu, Digestive Issues, Mild Hypertension, Pain Management, Pain management etc.</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_t6ByVK": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": " Is mad honey good for blood pressure?",
            "answer": "<p>The <a href=\"/pages/grayanotoxin\" title=\"Grayanotoxin I & II\">Grayanotoxin </a>present in Mad Honey can help temporarily lower the blood pressure however it may not be the best way to lower the pressure in the long run.</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_rhJPdN": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Does Mad Honey heal cancer?",
            "answer": "<p>No, mad honey doesn’t heal cancer but some test-tube studies suggest andromedotoxin (a grayanotoxin) and other rhododendron extracts might slow cancer cell growth (e.g., liver, breast cancer cells.</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_ULXymf": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Is the use of mad honey good for gastritis?",
            "answer": "<p>Yes, mad honey is good for gastritis. A Lab study showed Rhododendron honey may inhibit H. pylori (a bacteria linked to ulcers) (Journal of Ethnopharmacology, 2015). Also, it has been traditionally used at tiny doses for stomach pain, acid reflux, gastric ulcers.</p>"
          }
        },
        "text_6KVEYi": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Can Mad Honey enhance sexual health?",
            "answer": "<p>Although the Mad Honey has been used traditionally as an aphrodisiac, there is a myth regarding euphoria and sexual health. The Euphoric feeling can heighten sensations and pleasure making the sexual experience more enjoyable and satisfying.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
